The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Wednesday, September 07, 2005 

 IN THE CITY

 Having almost resigned to the fact that they have to lose the CFL Premier Division title to Mohun Bagan, East Bengal coach Subhas Bhowmick are approaching the upcoming Federation Cup in a big way. This is one of the trophies Bhowmick failed to win during his association with the club. 

 It has been learnt that the club is planning to conduct a conditioning camp in Santiniketan ahead of the Federation Cup, slated in New Delhi in October. 

 Meanwhile, Bhowmick may leave for Brazil on September 15. He is going on the tour in a move to learn more about modern-day coaching. 

 South Eastern Railway (SER) emerged champions in the men?s section of the all-India Railway table tennis championships on Tuesday. They beat Eastern Railway 3-2 in the final. Anirban Nandy, Amit Das and Soumyajit Sarkar represented South Eastern Railway.

 Central Railway ? represented by Leena Medhekar, Mamta Prabhu and Deepali Javeri ? bagged the women?s title defeating South Eastern Railway 3-1. 

 The A.N. Ghosh Trophy may turn out to be a three-day affair from this season. The CAB is considering this proposal and, if accepted, the meet may begin during the last week of October. CAB is planning to use this meet for preparation of Ranji Trophy.

 Hindalco got the better of ITC Limited in their match of the fourth corporate indoor cricket tournament at Space Circle on Monday. 

 Taldi Swimming Centre will organise a one-day waterpolo meet on Sunday. About 150 players are expected to take part in the meet. 

 SQUASH: Calcutta International meet at Racket Club.

 TABLE TENNIS: All Bengal me-et at Sabuj Sangha from 11 am.




